	<h2>Highlights</h2>

	<ol>
		<li>
			<strong>Castiglione del Lago Old Town</strong><br />
			Take your time strolling the beautiful streets, browsing boutique shops, and stopping for a gelato or a bite to eat. If you’re in town around the hour, listen out for the bell tower ringing—kids especially love hearing it chime as you wander.
		</li>

		<li>
	<strong>Palazzo della Corgna (Palace + walls)</strong><br />
	The Palazzo della Corgna is a Renaissance palace commissioned in the mid‑1500s by Ascanio della Corgna, during the period when the della Corgna family ruled the town
	(<a href="https://www.palazzodellacorgna.it/?lang=en" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">official site</a>).
	It’s a great “one afternoon” activity: tour the palace rooms and art, then walk along the walls for lake views. In summer, there are often outdoor film nights shown against the backdrop of the fortress walls.
</li>
		<li>
			<strong>Café Pescatore (Praia / lake / beach access)</strong><br />
			A must‑visit for lake views and a beach vibe. Great for a morning coffee and a dip, while kids can play on the grass or in the playground. Also ideal for lunch or a pre‑dinner drink—cocktails are excellent. Sun loungers are available to rent, and you can rent kayaks and pedal boats to get out on the lake.
		</li>

		<li>
			<strong>Outdoor swimming pool – Camping Listro</strong><br />
			A brilliant afternoon option to cool down and relax. The pool is within a campsite and is accessible to non‑camping guests (you mentioned ~€5 per person), typically including pool access plus parasols and sunbeds. There’s also a mini supermarket and café/bar/restaurant onsite, and a green area by the lake with a small playground (and go‑karts for kids). Bring a passport on your first visit—staff may ask for one.
		</li>

		<li>
			<strong>Ferry / Pier (Castiglione del Lago)</strong><br />
			This is where you catch the boat to Isola Maggiore, and it’s also a lovely place to start a lakeside promenade walk—especially around golden hour.
		</li>
	</ol>

